problem_statement.RootCause:
1) sympy/matrices/matrices.py -> MatrixProperties.is_upper (lines ~1113–1115): the implementation uses the generator expression

    return all(self[i, j].is_zero
               for i in range(1, self.rows)
               for j in range(i))

   This encodes the implicit assumption that every j produced by range(i) is a valid column index (j < self.cols). For tall matrices (rows > cols) this is false; the expression can yield j >= self.cols and thus attempts to access non-existent columns.

   Correct relationship (diagnostic): the inner loop bound must be limited by the number of columns. The intended set of column indices to check for a given row i is j in range(min(i, self.cols)).

2) sympy/matrices/matrices.py -> MatrixProperties._eval_is_upper_hessenberg (lines ~641–644): the implementation uses

    return all(self[i, j].is_zero
               for i in range(2, self.rows)
               for j in range(i - 1))

   This likewise assumes that j in range(i - 1) is always a valid column index (j < self.cols). For tall matrices this can produce j >= self.cols and thus indexing attempts that raise IndexError.

   Correct relationship (diagnostic): the inner loop bound should be j in range(min(i - 1, self.cols)).

3) Index validation and error surface: indexing flows through DenseMatrix.__getitem__ (sympy/matrices/dense.py) and ultimately to a2idx (sympy/matrices/matrices.py). The a2idx implementation enforces column bounds and raises the observed error message when a column index is out of range:

    def a2idx(j, n=None):
        ...
        if n is not None:
            if j < 0:
                j += n
            if not (j >= 0 and j < n):
                raise IndexError("Index out of range: a[%s]" % (j,))

   Example observed error (consistent with the stack trace): 'IndexError: Index out of range: a[2]' when evaluating sympy.zeros(4, 2).is_upper because the generator produced j == 2 while self.cols == 2.

